From: 4noha
Subject: bus_space_notimpl.S: 4-byte align panic strings (clang-22 cross-build prereq)
License: ISC (this patch modifies OpenBSD source and inherits ISC; see ../LICENSE-ISC)

bus_space_notimpl.S: 4-byte align panic strings (clang-22 cross-build
prerequisite).

This is NOT a functional fix: it is the prerequisite for cross-building
armv7 GENERIC on an arm64 OpenBSD build VM using the pkg clang-22
toolchain. Native builds with the OpenBSD base clang (19) on the DM250
itself do not need this (the bcmbt-only kernel built fine with base
clang on the device).

Problem:
  On the build VM with ~/bin/cc = clang-22 (-target arm-unknown-openbsd7.9)
  building GENERIC, bus_space_notimpl.o fails to assemble:
    /tmp/bus_space_notimpl-XXXX.s: error: Relocation not aligned
      adr r4, Lbs_notimpl_bs_X_text ; ... .asciz "X" ; .align 0 ;
  The NOT_IMPL macro emits an odd-length .asciz followed by `.align 0`
  (no alignment). The next stub function therefore starts on an unaligned
  address, the `adr` target (the string label) becomes unaligned, and
  clang-22's stricter integrated-as rejects the adr relocation.

Fix:
  Change `.align 0` to `.align 2` (4-byte) at the end of the NOT_IMPL
  macro so each stub is aligned. Adds a tiny amount of padding; harmless
  otherwise.

Target: sys/arch/arm/arm/bus_space_notimpl.S NOT_IMPL macro.

--- sys/arch/arm/arm/bus_space_notimpl.S.orig
+++ sys/arch/arm/arm/bus_space_notimpl.S
@@ NOT_IMPL macro tail @@
 	adr	r4, LNAME(__C(func,_text))			;	\
 	b	bs_notimpl_panic				;	\
 	LLABEL(__C(func,_text))					;	\
 	.asciz	__S(func)					;	\
-	.align	0						;
+	.align	2						;

Verification: bus_space_notimpl.S assembles standalone with clang-22
(ELF 32-bit ARM output).
